h3. Summary
When using a *Page Properties Report* macro, some of the columns become wrapped, splitting the words into multiple lines.

h3. Steps to reproduce
# Create a page *A* and add a *Page Properties* macro with some content within it, making sure to add some columns;
# Publish this page;
# Create a page *B*;
# Add a *Page Properties Report* macro, pointing to page *A*;
# Publish the page;

h3. Expected Results
Carriage returns should only happen where a word would naturally break. If the *Page Properties Report* macro is too wide for the screen, then a scrollbar should appear, allowing the user to scroll horizontally to read the rest of the report.

h3. Actual results
The text within the columns is broken up into letters, causing the column to wrap and be illegible and the table width should fit the layout in a page properties macro.

h3. Workaround
Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

*Summary*
When adding a *Content Report Table* macro on a global template, it is not possible to set the field *Space* (from the macro) to fill as the current space as default when using the template on a space.

*Steps to Reproduce*
# Go to the Global Templates of your instance;
# Create a new global template;
# Insert a title and the Content Report Table;
# On the macro settings set a label;
# Save it;
# Create a page using this template.

Expected results:
You are able to set a kind of template variable on the Content Report Table macro when creating the template, so when you use the template, there is no need to add this information manually on the macro.
